edu.asu.ying.mapreduce.table

Class ClientTable

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.asu.ying.mapreduce.table.ClientTable
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Distributable, ElementSink, java.io.Serializable, java.util.Map<java.io.Serializable,java.io.Serializable>

    public final class ClientTable
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.Map<java.io.Serializable,java.io.Serializable>, Distributable, ElementSink, java.io.Serializable
    ClientTable is the heart of the P2P database on the client (issuing) side.

    Individual key->value (Element objects) are added to the table, which separates them into pages based on a predetermined number of elements per page.

    Full pages are distributed across the network so that a complete table exists only as the sum of all of the pages on the network holding that table's ID.

    The table object is a proxy to the distributed tables with regards to retrieval. Requesting a key from the table (Map.get(java.lang.Object)) initiates a lookup for the page holding that key. When the appropriate page is found, the value associated with the key is requested from the node holding that page.

    The table is therefore a lazily-populated hash table wherein each bucket exists on a separate physical node.

    A distributed filesystem could be implemented by creating a table with a page size of 1, wherein each key is a filename and each value is its contents. Each file would then be distributed to a different node.

    See Also:
    Page, Element, Serialized Form
